?PAELLA FEAST for 4? from @jaleobyjose 

Last weekend we invited Stephen’s parents to join us for this amazing take-out paella feast. They live in Colombia ?? but they have been stuck in the US because of COVID, so we‘ve gotten to see a lot more of them this summer!

We had a late lunch feast, ate every last bit, and it kept us full all day! So much delicious food. For $30 per person this is a steal. 

You can choose between a few types of Paella, so we decided to switch it up from the normal seafood and tried the Chicken and Mushroom, and DAMN, it was SO GOOD!! You know I love seafood, but DON’T SLEEP ON CHICKEN AND MUSHROOM PAELLA. It was SO flavorful. And between the two salad choices we highly recommend the MANCHEGO AND GREEN APPLE ???

Swipe for the full spread! ?? This feast serves up to four and features: Your choice of Paella served with tapas to share including Gazpacho, Tortilla de Patatas, your choice of Ensalada Manzanas con Hinojo y Queso Manchego or Ensalada Verde, flauta bread, and Flan for dessert for $120 (P.S. it comes in the paella pan and you get to keep it)! Note: we added the fresh cilantro ourselves!

Available for take-out or delivery from the DC and Crystal City @jaleobyjose locations.

node.text:
"The art of happiness is also and at the same time the art of knowing how to suffer well." ~ Thich Nhat Hanh ⁠
⁠
Do you ever find that somehow certain books or messages seem to cross our paths at the exact "right time"?? ??‍????‍??⁠
⁠
Frequently this seems to happen to me and our current book club selection ~  No Mud, No Lotus: The Art of Transforming Suffering, by Thich Nhat Hanh ~ is no exception.?⁠
⁠
I'll admit, initially I hesitated to step into a book about suffering. It seemed that given all that's unfolded in these past 6 months - the uncertainty, pandemic, job losses, explosion in Beirut, amongst a multitude of other "sufferings" - the last thing I wanted to do was read a book with this focus.?⁠
⁠
This type of initial hesitation, avoidance or turning away from the unwanted, the unpleasant is a very natural thing - something I work on within self and with clients regularly. None of us want to suffer - of course - however, we do want to experience the other side of things. So ultimately I choose to open the book, to learn more, with intention, about the art of knowing how to suffer well... ⁠
⁠
Not surprisingly - it has been exactly what I needed at this time! ?⁠
⁠
Perhaps you personally are suffering or are witnessing the suffering of others... In this read, #ThichNhatHanh offers the simple reminder that even brief moments of recognizing that suffering is here can help us shift into a state of greater ease. He guides us to "stop, follow our breathing, and acknowledge it. Don't try to deny uncomfortable emotions or push them down". ⁠
⁠
?May you find support in this simple mantra: ⁠
⁠
"Breathing in, I know suffering is there. Breathing out, I say hello to my suffering." ⁠
⁠

node.text:
Some things happen for a reason, other things happen spontaneously , other things catch you off guard, but most glorious and admirable things happen when you weren't planning on paying much attention to them, like a plant so green that sometimes you forget to care for, but still lives and gives generously, or like a sunflower praying and asking for more warmth from the sun, or mostly like the Nightingale who pierced her heart in the roots of a White Rose so it'll turns red to give it to the Boy who was in love when all he needed was a Red Rose. Oscar Wilde knew exactly how love heals more than it does hurt, how sometimes it really does hurt, how sacrifices are made and how the purest thing God has given us is love. Some things are patient and giving, just like people are, some others are simply not. Some people would listen to your apologies and expect the best from you, some people would apologize even when they did not do anything wrong, like removing the thorns from the rose you plucked and have your smooth silky fingers bleed but still would want to give it to someone you love, some people would love and long for you when all you want is to be loved, some people would hold your hand and lay still with you where all you can see is the beautiful blue sky and feel the sun shining on your face,sometimes all those people are one person , someone so heavenly , someone so lovable , someone like you. 
( I am an Arab author, I wrote my first book and published it on Amazon, would be grateful if you took a look at the link in my bio to see more )??? Thank you

node.text:
BIRTHDAY RECAP...

It was a strange time for me. My first without one of my lifelong birthday buddies...my Uncle Kent. Every year I would call him on the 7th. He would end with...talk to you on the 18th. As promised, he would call me and launch into..."CindyLou! CindyLouuuu. Her name is Cindy CindyLou! CindyLou!" And as I cracked up, filled with joy and delight...he would say, "Happy Birthday, Baby!!!" For the first time in my life...I couldnt look forward to that. I couldnt count on it. The call never came...as I had to brace myself, knowing it would never come again. My Uncle Kent passed April 4th...due to #Covid19. He was 59. Too too young.

This #birthday...I felt even more #grateful and happy to still be alive. There wasn't anything elaborate I wanted. Just to talk to/interact with good people, people I love and care about...eat some good food...enjoy my annual #Carvel cake and spend time at my #beach. Mission accomplished.

Sagarottara Kannadigaru Forum hosting a very unique talk show with Dr. D. Veerendra Heggade, Dharmadhikari, Sri Kshethra Dharmasthala on this Sunday (23rd August 2020) in which kannadigas residing in more than 55 countries in the world going to interact!

Chandrashekara Lingadalli (UAE), President of the Forum, Gopal Kulkarni (UK), Vice President, Hemegowda Madhu (Italy), Organising Secretary, Ravi Mahadeva (Saudi Arabia), Joint Secretary, Basava patil (UK), Treasurer will coordinate the event.

Sagarothara Kannadigaru Forum planning to rope in all legends of Kannada literary world. node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by @relatales on August 22, 2020 tagging @paper___in_____ashes. Image may contain: text that says 'E S LESSONS FROM LORD GANESHA -SRILEKHA MITRA Coretale Writer'.

Photo by @relatales on August 22, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'RELATALES 1.The Sense of Responsibility We are all familiar with the story of Lord Shiva beheading Ganesha which resulted in Ganesha's elephant head. The story teaches us that duty and responsibility are above everything else. Lord Ganesha readily sacrificed his head to fulfil the responsibility which his mother gave to him.'.

Photo by @relatales on August 22, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'RELATALES 2.Be A Good Listener Ganesha's ears symbolise the role of effective communication. A good listener always has a better understanding of the situation at hand. In decision-making, listening to others helps you analyse the situation from a different perspective and hence, guides you to a better solution.'.

Photo by @relatales on August 22, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'RELATALES 3.Power Should Be In Control Absolute power corrupts absolutely. The trunk of Ganesha is always rolled up in a certain manner. This suggests that he is in control of the power he wields. This is a lesson for us to have control of our powers and make good use of it.'.

Photo by @relatales on August 22, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'RELATALES 4.The Art of Forgiveness Once Lord Ganesha was invited to a feast and because of his enormous appetite, ate almost all the food. While returning, the moon mocked his bulging belly and laughed. Ganesha cursed the moon to be invisible. The moon realised its mistake and asked for forgiveness. Lord Ganesha immediately forgave the moon and proclaimed that the moon would grow thinner each day and remain invisible on one day of the month. Hence we learn the art of forgiveness from the God of wisdom.'.

Photo by @relatales on August 22, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'ELATALE 5.Humility and Respect for Other Beings The best example of this is Ganesha's ride. The huge God rides a puny mouse. It shows that the Lord doesn't discriminate and respects even the tiniest creature. This trait is crucial for us and should be imbibed.'.
